Deep Learning NLP : Natural Language Processing
¶

Project 8 DL NLP Airline Sentiment Classification
¶

Goal: Create a Classifier Model Capable of determining Airline Customers' Sentiments as Positive, Negative, Neutral.¶

Data Description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:
The project is from a dataset from Kaggle. Link to the Kaggle project site: https://www.kaggle.com/crowdflower/twitter-airline-sentiment. However, for this project's purpose the dataset has already been provided in a flat file "Tweets.csv", so no need to download from its original soure at Kaggle website.

The dataset has the following columns:
¶
No. Column Names No. Column Names No. Column Names.
01. tweet_id 06. airline 11. text
02. airline_sentiment 07. airline_sentiment_gold 12. tweet_coord
03. airline_sentiment_confidence 08. name 13. tweet_created
04. negativereason 09. negativereason_gold 14. tweet_location
05. negativereason_confidence 10. retweet_count 15. user_timezone

# Build Stop Words List: 

stp_wrd = stopwords.words('english')  # Get Standard Stop Words 

# Customize stopwords list by removing negative words ('no', 'not', 'nor') from the Standard Stopword List, 
# Because these words can change the meaning of the message, hence we WANT to KEEP these words in the 'text'. 

# These -ve words are NOT in Standard Stopwords. So we are ok, no need to remove these: none, nobody, nothing, neither, nowhere, never.

# These words have already been taken care of because we did 'Contractions' before removing Special Chars: 
# So no need to remove these words from Stopwords because the df 'text' will not have these words after applying 'Contractions':
#    "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn', "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', 
#    "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',"mustn't", 'needn', "needn't", 'shan', "shan't", 'shouldn', 
#    "shouldn't", 'wasn',"wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]

stpw_cust = ['no', 'not', 'nor']  # Custom Stopword list as per notes above

print('\n * Classification Report: \n\n', classification_report(y_test, result))

cm_TfidfV = confusion_matrix(y_test, result)

⬇ Understanding & Observations:

  1. No Missing / Null / NA Values. There is Data Imbalance Negatives: 9k+, Neutral: 3k+, Positives 2k+, Dup.Rows = 188 (Deleted).

  2. Tweets Chars Stats Per Tweet / Message:

    • Before Preprocess: Total Count/Sum = 1,504,724 Min = 12 Mean = 104 Max = 186
    • After Preprocess: Total Count/sum = 925,173 Min = 05 Mean = 64 Max = 131 (Overall Reduction).

  1. After html tag removal: Removed URLs, Accented Chars, Applied Contractions (These were not specified in the Problem Statement Steps). If we had NOT removed Accented chars then Contractions would have FAILED and may Lemmatizations too.

  2. Special chars & Punctuations were removed AFTER contractions and before tokenization: If we had removed Puncutations BEFORE Contractions then the Contractions would have Failed converting words such as "don't", "would't", etc...

  3. Stopwords: Added: "no", "not", "nor" to the Standard stop words list: Because these words can change the meaning of a Sentiment in the Message. These words are NOT present in the Standard Stopword list. If we had NOT used STOPWORDS then cetain Pronouns & Preposition words which has no NLP value, like "I, we, have, you, me, to the, at, for, in, off, on, over, under", etc... would have stayed in the text which would UnNECESSARILY increased the Bag Of Words count and the resulting Features and Dimensions. Hence, Using STOPWORDS is highly recommended as it will reduce the Dimensionality and make the NLP for Effective & Objective towards the GOAL which in this case is "Sentiment Analysis" which is least impacted by the STOPWORDS, hence REMOVE the Stopwords.

  4. Lemmatizer was used instead of Stemming: Because (WordNet) Lemmatizer gives a Meaningful Word Root/Stem which it Validates against a Standard Language (English) Dictionary. While a Stemmer just give the Root/Stem of a given Word even though its a meaningless word which may not be even in a standard language (English) dictionary.

  5. Count & TfIdf Vectorizer was used to extract 1000 Top features Max: Because increasing Max Words to 3k, 5k or greater, significantly increase the processing time but the NLP results may not increase proportionally or very significantly.

  6. Random Forest Classifier Model was used on each of the Two Vectorized Datasets for 1.Count and 2.Tf_Idf Vectorization which were Split (Train 70% / Test 30%) Separately each time before RFC Modelling and were Modelled Separately.

  7. Random Forest Classifier Model: CV Scores & Accuracies on Train & Test for TfIdf Vector are slightly better than "Count Vector" Datasets:

    • Count Vector: Test Accuracy: 0.721171 Train Accuracy: 0.770956 * CV Score: 0.705024
    • TfIDF Vector: Test Accuracy: 0.724861 Train Accuracy: 0.778766 * CV Score: 0.707031 <== Slightly Better Results Overall

Note: I attempted several way (RFC Parameters) to increase TEST Accuracies but it stayed in 7x% (0.7x) range, even though TRAIN Accuracies had gone up to high 90s% which was a diffrence of 20% point between Train & Test (Highly Overfitting). So I tweeked further to bring Train & Test numbers resonably close to each other. Hence the Train numbers came down to 70s% from 90s% so that its not Highly OverFitted. I also tried AdaBoost & GradientBoost Classifiers with several various Parameter combinations. I have removed the Code & Output from these Trial, Experiments, Attempts so as to reduce the non significant clutter from this Project's Code Notebook.

  1. Airline personnel should improve their Customer Interaction: A major share of Negative Reviews as about Bad inflight Service, Rudeness with Customers on Ground and issues about Rebooking flights.

  2. Flight Delays maybe beyond Airline's control, which is one of the top reasons for Negative Reviews, in which case airline can offer other accomodations and/or perks to Pacify Customers and avoid their -ve reviews.

    • Airline can stratigize the Neutrals Reviewers (Customers) who are on the fence (borderline) to make them happy so they can give Positive Reviews.
    • Meaning, try to Convert Neutral Customer so they write Positive Reviews, which would be much easier than converting Negative Reviewers to Positive ones.
